{"author":"RebarBotNava","data":{"fields":{"description":"RED baseline test suite: inject the full LLM-failure matrix through the pydantic-ai `model_override` seam and pin rebar's CURRENT behavior, so later stories flip it to the new behavior with a regression net.\n\n## Why\nBefore changing behavior we must pin what rebar does today for every failure class and prove the offline injection harness works. Verified on pydantic-ai 1.107.0: a `FunctionModel` that raises `ModelHTTPError(429, model_name, body)` propagates the error with `status_code` intact UP TO the runner's `except Exception` seam (`runner.py:353`), where it is CURRENTLY collapsed into `LLMUnavailableError` — so \"propagates unwrapped\" describes the pydantic-ai model→runner path, and the runner-level CURRENT behavior this suite pins is the collapse. A canned `finish_reason` is readable at `result.response.finish_reason`, and `httpx.ReadTimeout` reaches the same runner seam and is likewise collapsed today.\n\n## What\nA parametrized RED test file `tests/unit/test_llm_failure_matrix.py` injecting each failure class via a raising or canned pydantic-ai `FunctionModel` through the `PydanticAIRunner(model_override=...)` / `get_runner(override=...)` seams (`src/rebar/llm/runner.py:159,404`), asserting current behavior at two levels: (1) runner classification (everything collapses to `LLMUnavailableError` / `LLMRunnerError` today) and (2) gate end-to-end (plan-review systemic → INDETERMINATE + claim blocked; completion → fail-closed; code-review). Guarded by `pydantic_ai.models.ALLOW_MODEL_REQUESTS = False`.\n\n## Scope\n- **Failure matrix** (each injected via `FunctionModel`): 429-rate, 429-insufficient_quota (body), 529, 500/503, `httpx.ConnectTimeout`, `httpx.ReadTimeout`, 401/403, 400 bad-request, 400 context-length, 413, `content_filter` finish_reason, length/truncation, unparseable output, validation-retry exhaustion, `UsageLimitExceeded`, `tool_calls_limit`, unknown exception. HTTP-status failures are injected by raising `pydantic_ai.exceptions.ModelHTTPError(status_code, model_name, body)`.\n- **Third-party exception classes are imported, not code-grounded against rebar `src/`.** `ContentFilterError` and `IncompleteToolCall` are PYDANTIC-AI library exceptions (NOT rebar symbols) used to distinguish a structured content-filter/incomplete-tool signal from the raw `content_filter` finish_reason. They are VERIFIED importable at pydantic-ai 1.107.0 — reproduce: `python -c \"from pydantic_ai.exceptions import ContentFilterError, IncompleteToolCall\"` (exits 0, no error). The test imports them from `pydantic_ai.exceptions`; a plan-review code-grounding pass that greps only rebar `src/`/`tests/` will not find them and must not be read as \"the symbol is absent\" (the known code-blind-reviewer false-positive, same class the epic settled for the `[retries]` extra). If a future pin ever drops a symbol, the import fails loudly at collection time — that IS the regression signal, not a rebar-side defect.\n- **`UsageLimitExceeded` fixture uses the DERIVED limit, not the literal 50.** The runner does NOT use pydantic-ai's default `request_limit=50`: it derives `request_limit = max(1, math.ceil(cfg.max_iterations / 2))` at `runner.py:310` (and `tool_calls_limit = max(8, cfg.max_iterations)`). The looping-model fixture MUST set `cfg.max_iterations` explicitly and assert against the derived value — e.g. `max_iterations=6 → request_limit=3` — never a bare `50`. A separate case sets a low `max_iterations` so `tool_calls_limit` (`max(8, max_iterations)`) is the operative cap for a re-calling tool.\n- **Two-scope scenarios:** systemic (whole op) vs per-criterion (one unit among N). The per-criterion fail-open is a PLAN-REVIEW property (one flaky finder among N marks that criterion INDETERMINATE and the review continues — `pass1.py:453`); the systemic block-but-degraded posture is asserted for ALL THREE gates (plan-review → INDETERMINATE verdict; completion → fail-closed; code-review → systemic). The per-criterion case is exercised on plan-review only (the gate that has N independent units); systemic is exercised on all three.\n- Named liveness scenarios pin CURRENT (pre-change) behavior only: a hung model request and a hung tool document that TODAY there is no per-request/per-tool timeout (the RED test asserts the current unbounded/hanging behavior via a short outer test-level guard), and a looping model reaches the runner's DERIVED `request_limit`. The NEW abort+classify assertions are added by story chief-contained-hoopoe's tests, NOT here — this baseline must stay green on today's code.\n- Guard tests: `--force` / `--force-close` / feature-disabled never enters the handling path.\n- Coverage boundary: `model_override` injects at the pydantic-ai MODEL layer, ABOVE the httpx transport where the retry lives — so transport-layer retry is NOT exercisable here; it is covered by the transport-injection spike in story morbid-uncultured-arcticduck.\n- NOT in scope: the NEW behavior (asserted GREEN by later stories) — this story pins CURRENT behavior only.\n\n## Acceptance Criteria\n- [ ] A parametrized test file `tests/unit/test_llm_failure_matrix.py` exercises every failure class via `model_override`, offline, guarded by `ALLOW_MODEL_REQUESTS=False`; `make test` runs it green on TODAY's code.\n- [ ] Each parametrized case carries an inline `# CURRENT(<file>:<line>): <one-line behavior>` comment naming the exact source location whose behavior it pins (e.g. `# CURRENT(runner.py:365): provider exceptions collapse to LLMUnavailableError`). \"Source citation\" = that inline `file:line` comment (documentation of the pinned seam, not a runtime assertion); its presence on every case is checked by a meta-test that asserts a `# CURRENT(` marker exists for each parametrized id.\n- [ ] The pydantic-ai library exceptions used by the matrix (`ModelHTTPError`, `ContentFilterError`, `IncompleteToolCall`, `UsageLimitExceeded`, `UnexpectedModelBehavior`) are imported from `pydantic_ai.exceptions` at module top; an absent symbol fails collection loudly.\n- [ ] The `UsageLimitExceeded`/`tool_calls_limit` cases set `cfg.max_iterations` explicitly and assert against the DERIVED `request_limit = max(1, ceil(max_iterations/2))` / `tool_calls_limit = max(8, max_iterations)` (runner.py:310-314), never a hardcoded 50.\n- [ ] Two-scope coverage: the per-criterion fail-open is asserted on PLAN-REVIEW (one INDETERMINATE unit among N does not block); the systemic degraded posture is asserted on plan-review, completion, AND code-review. Force/disabled guard scenarios are covered.\n- [ ] The file is the named baseline that later stories flip to the new behavior; `make lint`/`make typecheck`/`make test` green."}},"env_id":"ade0f2ef-51cc-45a2-bb97-c09846cd3df5","event_type":"EDIT","timestamp":1783627806542334001,"uuid":"16fcafcd-c4a8-4646-bf69-92beba384e5a"}